Let us next consider how not only the hot springs of Bath but all thermal springs acquire their heat. With regard to the heat of thermal springs, 1 cannot agree with those who maintain that their heat is due to warmth communicated by subterranean fire. For if any fire ol this sort burned in the bowels of the earth, it would certainly betray itself by its flame bursting out somewhere; since indeed a continual influx of air is absolutely necessary for the mainten- ance of fire. But granting that there are subterranean lires, how is it,I ask, that they are not extinguished by the waters which they are supposed to heatl And whence should the material be supplied sor- maintaining a fire so vast and enduringl

Wherefore, since it is not probable that the hot springs are heated by subterranean lires, we may maintain with our learned countryman, Jordan, that the warming of the hot springs originates in fermentation excited sornewhere in the bowels of the earth. But to understand how this fermentation is produced the following must be premised.

In the first place, then, it may reasonably be supposed that at any rate most fountains derive their origin from rain-water.
